%
What is more important in determining an (individual) organism's phenotype,
its genes or its environment?
  Any developmental biologist knows that this is a meaningless question.
Every aspect of an organism's phenotype is the joint product of its genes
and its environment. To ask which is more important is like asking, Which
is more important in determining the area of a rectangle, the length or the
width? Which is more important in causing a car to run, the engine or the
gasoline? Genes allow the environment to influence the development of
phenotypes.
        -- Tooby and Cosmides
