You can make a small program (say, 1,000 lines) work through brute force
even when breaking every rule of good style. For a larger program, this is
simply not so. If the structure of a 100,000-line program is bad, you will
find that new errors are introduced as fast as old ones are removed.
        -- Bjarne Stroustrup
%
Take the bettors in the racetrack experiment. Thirty seconds before putting
down their money, they had been tentative and uncertain; thirty seconds
after the deed, they were significantly more optimistic ans self-assured.
The act of making a final decision--in this case, of buying a ticket--had
been the critical factor. Once a stand had been taken, the need for
consistency pressured these people to bring what they felt and believed
into line with what they had already done. They simply convinced themselves
that they had made the right choice and, no doubt, felt better and it all.
        -- Robert B. Cialdini, Influence: The Psychology of Persuasion
