Through the discovery of Buchner, Biology was relieved of yet another
fragment of mysticism. The splitting up of sugar into CO2 and alcohol is no
more the effect of a vital principle than the splitting up of cane sugar by
invertase. The history of this problem is instructive, as it warns us
against considering problems beyond our reach because they have not yet
found their solution.
        -- Jacques Loeb, 1906, on the discovery of the mechanism of
