%
Nothing in life is certain except death, taxes and the second law of
thermodynamics. All three are processes in which useful or accessible forms
of some quantity, such as energy or money, are transformed into useless,
inaccessible forms of the same quantity. That is not to say that these
three processes don't have fringe benefits: taxes pay for roads and
schools; the second law of thermodynamics drives cars, computers and
metabolism; and death, at the very least, opens up tenured faculty
positions.
        -- Seth Lloyd
